# Accepted findings — see reasoning below. Re-evaluate if the underlying
# code changes (e.g. the chart's securityContext defaults, or this becomes
# a network-facing service).

# Dockerfile: no HEALTHCHECK instruction.
# This image runs a Slack bot worker process (long-lived outbound connection),
# not a service with an HTTP endpoint to probe — a container-level HEALTHCHECK
# doesn't apply the way it would to a web server.
DS-0026

# Helm chart (charts/kubeai-chatbot/templates/deployment.yaml):
# runAsUser/runAsGroup > 10000 recommendation. The chart intentionally pins
# UID/GID 1000 to match the Dockerfile's non-root `kubeai` user
# (groupadd -g 1000 / useradd -u 1000), which owns the mounted volumes.
KSV-0020
KSV-0021

# Non-default namespace recommendation. The chart doesn't hardcode a
# namespace — it's supplied at install time (`helm install -n <namespace>`);
# this only fires because Trivy renders the chart without a namespace override.
KSV-0110

# "Uses the default security context" — the chart already sets an explicit,
# hardened securityContext via values.yaml (allowPrivilegeEscalation: false,
# capabilities dropped, readOnlyRootFilesystem, runAsNonRoot, runAsUser).
KSV-0118

# Untrusted registry image. The image repository is configurable via
# `values.yaml` (image.repository) per deployment, not a fixed third-party
# registry baked into the chart.
KSV-0125
